	INSTRUCTIONS
    --================--

	The Guardian's Play is one kind of patience. It may feel a bit
confusing at the first, but when you learn to play it, it becomes even
too easy (?). Rules are simple. Your mission is to adjust 48 cards in
order in the middle. There are four ace's, where you are going to build
your stacks. On these ace's your pile can start like: A, 2, 3, 4...
OR like: A, K, Q, J... So, on the ace you can put a card which is
labeled either K or 2. Simple? Note: On the stack of spades you can
ONLY put cards from the same land ( = spades).

	Now there are several places, where you can store your cards
occasionally. There are eight piles of cards which contains five cards
each. The maximum of the size of these stacks is ten cards. "Building
rules" are almost the same as on the ace's. So for example if you have
5 at the top of the pile, you can build it to 4 or to 6. Again you must
must remember: On the hearts you can move only those cards which are
also labeled as hearts. Got it?!

	If one of these "five-card-stacks" runs out of cards (=is empty),
you can put there any card what you can get. This makes your playing
easier. And when you have something about three or more "free" stacks,
you will probably complete your sorting-mission.

	At the bottom of the screen there are eight cards at the beginning
of the playing-session. On these cards you CAN'T build any piles. You can
only take a cards from there. But there is one exeption. In the middle of
these eight cards there is "place" for one card (JAIL???). Once during the
game you can capture one card in this jail, and take it back when ever you
want to. This makes the game *much* easier, also.

	With there simple rules you should be ready to FACE THE THING
THAT SHOULD NOT BE... Oh yes. There is "Cards left" and "Moves" down there.
Well, you must allready know whatsda meaning of these... Temperature? Yes.

				We wish you  COOL PLAYINGS!!!!






	INTERFACE
    --=============--

	To play (to move cards) use the mouse. It doesn't matter which
mousebutton you push, they're equal. When you run this game, you will
enter to beginning-screen (nice name, invented by me!). In this screen you
are expected to press mousebutton to start playing. If you want to exit the
game then press ESC.

	During the playing you can get back to beginning-screen by pressing
ESC. The backspace is used to cancel you thoughts. So if you take a card
and then want to return it back to it's previos place then do it by pressing
backspace. Oh, cool. Now there are also those two gadgets labeled as 'QUIT'
and 'UNDO'. So QUIT=ESC and UNDO=Backspace. Got it?!







